==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Salad
<hw>Sal"ad</hw> <pr>(s⟦acr⟧l"⟦ait⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>salade</ets>, OIt. <ets>salata</ets>, It. <ets>insalata</ets>, fr.
<ets>salare</ets> to salt, fr. L. <ets>sal</ets> salt. See
<er>Salt</er>, and cf. <er>Slaw</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
preparation of vegetables, as lettuce, celery, water cress, onions,
etc., usually dressed with salt, vinegar, oil, and spice, and eaten for
giving a relish to other food; <as>as, lettuce <ex>salad</ex>; tomato
<ex>salad</ex>, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Leaves eaten raw are termed <qex>salad</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dish composed of chopped meat or fish, esp.
chicken or lobster, mixed with lettuce or other vegetables, and seasoned
with oil, vinegar, mustard, and other condiments; <as>as, chicken
<ex>salad</ex>; lobster <ex>salad</ex></as>.</def><-- mention mayonnaise
-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Salad burnet</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the common
burnet (<spn>Poterium Sanguisorba</spn>), sometimes eaten as a salad in
Italy.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Salad days</ent>⟦br⟧
